= Chapter 5: The Shimmering Harvest
\
The opening of the Grand Gateway triggered a golden age for Luminos-Vara.

Day after day, teams of brave citizen explorers marched through the towering deepslate frame into the Void Temple. They returned with wheelbarrows and iron crates piled high with glowing teal Echo Crystals.

The city had never been brighter or louder. Inventors used the crystals to build automated redstone street sweepers, musical fountains that played beautiful songs whenever someone walked past, and massive elevators that could carry whole crates of glow berries up from the deep farms without needing ropes.

Even the city's protectors got an upgrade. A dozens-strong army of pristine stone Wardens now patrolled the grand walkways, their crystalline hearts beating in a beautiful, synchronized rhythm. Whenever a rogue zombie or a stray skeleton wandered into the city from an dark cave, a Warden would hear it instantly, rush forward, and defeat the threat with a single sweep of its massive stone arms.

To the citizens, it seemed like they had built a perfect world. But Valen couldn't shake the feeling that something was wrong.

"Look at this, Master Elian," Valen said, holding up a small glass jar in the chief engineer’s crowded workshop. Inside the jar was a tiny piece of the dark blue moss Valen had scraped from his workshop floor.

As Elian talked, the moss inside the jar pulsed with a soft, eerie light.

"Ah, the void-moss," Elian said carelessly, not looking up from a complex redstone blueprint. "Don't worry about it, Valen. The explorers say it grows everywhere in the temple. It’s harmless. In fact, it seems to absorb sound, which makes the city much more peaceful!"

"But it's spreading," Valen pressed, his voice tight. "It's not just in my workshop anymore. It's growing behind the grand library. It’s creeping up the supports of the Grand Gateway. And... it does something weird when it hears a loud noise."

To demonstrate, Valen tapped the glass jar with his golden tuning fork. PING!

The moment the sound wave hit the jar, a tiny, bone-white horn growing out of the moss—a Skulk Shrieker—shivered. It let out a low, ghostly wail that sounded like a cold wind blowing through a graveyard.

Master Elian paused, a shiver running down his spine. He looked at the jar for a long moment, then shook his head and smiled. "A fascinating acoustic reaction! We must study it sometime. But not today, my boy. Today, we are installing the largest Echo Crystal core into our central power grid!"

Valen sighed, realizing no one was listening. The city was too drunk on its own success to notice the dark vines wrapping around its ankles.

That night, Valen decided to do some investigating on his own. He grabbed a blue soul torch and walked out into the central plaza.

The city was quiet, most citizens asleep in their deepslate homes. The Grand Gateway towered over the empty square, its massive blue vortex swirling silently. Standing guard at the base of the portal was one of the pristine stone Wardens. Its gray stone skin was clean, and its teal heart pulsed peacefully.

Valen walked up to the giant machine. "Are you feeling anything strange too?" he asked softly.

The Warden’s stone antenna twitched, turning toward Valen. It hummed a gentle, familiar tone, acknowledging its creator.

Suddenly, a strange sound echoed from a dark alleyway across the plaza. It wasn't the sound of a zombie or a citizen. It was a rhythmic, wet click... click... click...

The Warden’s head snapped toward the alley. Its antenna began to vibrate violently.

Valen held up his torch, stepping closer to the dark alleyway. The blue firelight illuminated the cobblestone. The street was completely gone. In its place was a thick, bubbling carpet of midnight-blue Skulk. It had grown completely over the deepslate blocks, swallowing the path.

In the middle of the skulk sat a massive, corrupted mass of dark tendrils and bone-like plates. It was a Skulk Catalyst.

As Valen watched in horror, a stray cave spider crawled out of the wall and stepped onto the skulk. Instantly, the Skulk Catalyst flashed with a blinding teal light. A strange, mystical energy burst out from the Catalyst, washing over the spider. The spider didn't just die—it dissolved into pure experience and sound energy, which the skulk greedily drank up. The dark moss instantly grew three feet wider, creeping closer to the plaza.

The stone Warden stepped forward, its programming telling it to protect the city. But as its massive stone feet stepped onto the edge of the skulk carpet, the machine stumbled.

The skulk didn't attack the Warden with teeth or claws. Instead, the tiny, fine tendrils of the dark moss began to climb up the Warden's pristine stone legs. The Warden’s crystal heart, which ran on the exact same sound energy that the skulk fed on, began to glitch.

The Warden let out a confused, distorted groan. The peaceful teal light in its chest flickered, turning a deeper, darker shade of midnight blue.

"No!" Valen gasped, rushing forward. "Get away from it!"

But the Warden didn't bow to him this time. As Valen shouted, the Warden's antenna twitched aggressively. It turned its faceless head toward Valen, and for the first time, its internal hum sounded angry, matching the deep, rumbling heartbeat of the trapped creature on the other side of the portal.